review_blob: For something called hop hazard, this is a remarkably full bodied, rich and malty beer.  I actually cant decide whether to grade this down for not being as hoppy as I want or grade it up for being so balanced.  Either way, a great APA and worthy of being a session beer.  Nice amber color too, although the head and lacing are only OK
beer_name: River Horse Hop Hazard Pale Ale

review_blob: this along with ayinger celebrator dopplebock is the only "roasty" beer that I actually like that I have tried.  While I was thinking it would have the stout-y chococlate/mocha/coffee taste, this was a totally "roasty" stout and had a great caramel aroma, but it didnt burn the palate and was approachable.  This is one of the few stouts that you could imagine getting a pitcher of...

This IPA looks pretty nice with good head retention, although not the best Ive ever seen.  The aroma isnt that strong and is kind of grassy/herbal.  The taste is better, but still has a little metallic twinge at the end which is kind of unpleasant.  However, for an IPA, this is nice and hoppy, actually very hoppy.  Worth a try

This is the type of IPA I like- more malty and fuller bodied - the head on this was best described as "mountainous."  The gripe I have about Racer 5 is that while it looks really good, it tastes tame for an IPA- especially because I wouldnt immediately describe it as hoppy.  I still like it more than most beers, and more than most IPAs, but as a hophead I kept wanting more bitterness and hop aroma.

man this IPA has a killer hop aroma- like you are sticking your nose into a bowl of hops!  The appearance is really nice too, as is most of the southern tier brews- a nice amber with good lacing- not so much thick but good retention.  The thing I like the best about this IPA is while it is not my favorite, it really accomplishes its brewers goal- to make an accessible yet authentic IPA.  Filtered and clean finish  wouldnt normally turn me on to an IPA, but this, like SNPA, is something I could show my macro-friends and convert them to hoppiness.

This was my first taste of a tripel- and I will be searching for more as a result.  I must say that this beer had the most amazing pillowy sticky gorgeous lacing I have ever seen on any beer regardless of style....awesome.  While this beer clocks in at 9 %abv, you arent overwhelmed by stinging alcohol at all- just another flavor in the mix.  Tastes mildy hoppy, thick and chewy with hints of alcohol.  Pretty good

Given the low rating on the site for this beer, I was hesitant to get a 6er of it, so I got Southern Tiers variety pack just to sample- but now I wish that I had gotten a 6!  This beer is reminiscant of Red Seal Ale- a surprisingly hoppy yet sweet APA.  The aroma jumped out of the bottle and I could smell this one across the room, but the appearance isnt that great and the lacing is kind of weak.  Still, a really tasty ale with more body and hops than you might expect
beer_name: Southern Tier PMX (Phin & Matts Extraordinary Ale)

review_blob: Doesnt quite live up to the hype, but is a really good IPA nonetheless.  Spicy hop aroma, good head retention and deep amber color- the flavor is the best part.  While it certainly does have an ample amount of hops - the biting taste lingers on the tongue- the part I like best is the bready malt taste that holds its own.  My main gripe against HopDevil is that its mouthfeel is kinda watery.  I actually can conceive of using it as a session beer, which shouldnt be the case with a 7% IPA.

this one surprised me....for an IPA, it was very citrusy and floral, and reminded me of wheat beer, not an IPA....for the true hop heads out there, try Arrogant Bastard ale from Stone, it is truly a bitter treat, but this offering seemed to be more sweet and fruity than what I expect from an IPA
